{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 23:30:04.064621", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Submission successful.\n\nSummary of submitted solution:\n- is_anomaly: true\n- faulty_devices: [ \"server_access_router\" ]\n- root_cause_name: [ \"ospf_area_misconfiguration\" ]\n\nRecommended immediate mitigation (actionable steps you can apply now):\n1. On server_access_router, remove or disable the advertisement of 10.200.0.0/24 into OSPF:\n   - If the prefix is being injected via a connected network statement or auto-interface advertisement, remove the network statement or change interface config so the LAN subnet is not redistributed.\n   - If the prefix is being redistributed from another protocol, stop redistribution or apply route-map/prefix-list to filter 10.200.0.0/24.\n2. If isolation must be preserved while keeping the server subnet locally routable for management:\n   - Implement access‑lists on server_access_router to deny traffic from user subnets (e.g., 10.1.0.0/16) to 10.200.0.0/24 while permitting necessary management networks and load balancer health checks.\n   - Alternatively, place backends in a separate VRF or apply static routes on core pointing to the load balancer only.\n3. Verify after change:\n   - From a user host, ping 10.200.0.3 should fail; ping to load balancer 10.200.0.7 should still succeed.\n   - Check OSPF route table on core routers to confirm 10.200.0.0/24 is no longer advertised.\n   - Validate application reachability through load balancer and that service behavior is unchanged.\n\nIf you want, I can now run the suggested investigative follow-ups (dump server_access_router FRR running-config, show ACLs, curl backend IPs from a user host) to gather exact commands/config lines to change.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 2391, "output_tokens": 384, "total_tokens": 2775, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 1664}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, 